# Video Script: "AI Coding Assistants: The Productivity Boom and the Junior Developer Question"

**Target runtime: 2:30–3:00**
**Speakers: Syed Mohammad Arif (A)**
**Format suggestion: screen-recorded slides with live voiceover (no AI-generated voices)**

---

### [0:00–0:15] HOOK

> "Every one of us in this room has probably had an AI tool finish a line of code before
> we did. Today we're looking at GitHub Copilot, Cursor, and tools like them — and at a
> question the entire software industry is arguing about right now: are these tools
> making developers faster, or are they quietly closing the door on junior developers
> like us?"

*(Slide: Title)*

---

### [0:15–0:45] WHAT'S HAPPENING

> "AI coding assistants have gone from a novelty to the default. As of the latest
> Stack Overflow survey, 84 percent of developers now use or plan to use AI tools in
> their workflow. GitHub Copilot alone has around 20 million users, and it's deployed
> at 90 percent of Fortune 100 companies. And Cursor — a newer AI-first code editor —
> went from 100 million dollars to 2 billion dollars in annual revenue in about a year
> and a half. That's one of the fastest growth curves any software company has ever had."

*(Slide: Adoption stats with big numbers)*

---

### [0:45–1:15] THE PRODUCTIVITY REALITY

> "So how much faster does it actually make us? Back in 2023, the pitch was that AI
> would make developers ten times more productive. The real 2026 numbers are more
> modest — and more interesting. Microsoft and Accenture studies found about a 26
> percent average productivity gain. Other independent reviews put GitHub Copilot
> around 30 to 40 percent faster on typical tasks. That's a real gain — just not the
> miracle that was promised. And there's a catch: research from DORA found that while
> AI makes individual developers feel faster, it can actually hurt team-wide delivery
> stability. Code also gets rewritten more often after being AI-generated than it used
> to. Only 29 percent of developers actually trust AI output, even though almost
> everyone uses it."

*(Slide: Productivity gain comparison — 10x hype vs ~26-40% reality, plus DORA split)*

---

### [1:15–2:00] THE CONTROVERSY

> "Here's where it gets serious for us specifically. A Stanford study found that
> employment for developers aged 22 to 25 has dropped almost 20 percent since AI tools
> took off. Entry-level software job postings are down by as much as 40 percent from
> their 2022 peak, and in the first two months of 2026 alone, new postings dropped
> another 15 percent. The reasoning companies give is simple: a small team of senior
> developers using Copilot or Cursor can now ship what used to take a much bigger team,
> including the juniors who used to handle the simpler, repetitive work."

> "But that's not the whole story. AWS CEO Matt Garman called the idea of replacing
> junior developers with AI 'one of the dumbest things' he's ever heard. His point:
> junior developers are the cheapest people on the team, they're the most comfortable
> with AI tools, and without them, companies eventually run out of senior engineers to
> promote. And it's not just talk — IBM just announced it's tripling entry-level hiring
> in the US for 2026, betting that juniors who work alongside AI are actually more
> valuable, not less."

*(Slide: Split screen — "The Cuts" vs "The Pushback")*

---

### [2:00–2:30] WHAT IT MEANS FOR US

> "So this isn't settled. The industry is genuinely split between companies shrinking
> their junior pipeline and companies investing in it. What is clear is what's being
> asked of entry-level developers is changing. AI skills now show up in 42 percent of
> software job postings, up from just 8 percent in 2022. The students who land these
> roles aren't necessarily the fastest typists — they're the ones who can direct an AI
> tool, catch its mistakes, and explain why the code works."

*(Slide: "What this means for us" — AI fluency stat + skills shift)*

---

### [2:30–2:50] CONCLUSION

> "AI coding assistants are not a side trend — they're already standard practice in the
> industry we're about to enter. The debate over junior jobs is real, and it's still
> playing out. But the lesson for us is the same either way: learning to work *with*
> these tools, not just around them, is quickly becoming a core part of the job
> description itself."

*(Slide: Closing / thank you)*

